SIMPLE: shining
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shining
<hw>Shin"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Emitting
light, esp. in a continuous manner; radiant; <as>as, <ex>shining</ex>
lamps</as>; also, bright by the reflection of light; <as>as,
<ex>shining</ex> armor</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Fish . . . with their fins and
<xex>shining</xex> scales.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Splendid; illustrious; brilliant; distinguished;
conspicious; <as>as, a <ex>shining</ex> example of
charity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Having the surface smooth and polished; -- said of
leaves, the surfaces of shells, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Glistening; bright; radiant; resplendent;
effulgent; lustrous; brilliant; glittering; splendid; illustrious.</syn>
-- <usage><er>Shining</er>, <er>Brilliant</er>, <er>Sparking</er>.
<xex>Shining</xex> describes the steady emission of a strong light, or
the steady reflection of light from a clear or polished surface.
<xex>Brilliant</xex> denotes a shining of great brightness, but with
gleams or flashes. <xex>Sparkling</xex> implies a fitful, intense
shining from radiant points or sparks, by which the eye is dazzled. The
same distinctions obtain when these epithets are figuratively applied. A
man of <xex>shining</xex> talents is made conspicious by possessing
them; if they flash upon the mind with a peculiarly striking effect, we
call them <xex>brilliant</xex>; if his brilliancy is marked by great
vivacity and occasional intensity, he is
<xex>sparkling</xex>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>True paradise . . . inclosed with <qex>shining</qex> rock.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some in a <qex>brilliant</qex> buckle bind her waist,⟦br⟧
Some round her neck a circling light display.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>sparkling</qex> blade about his head he blest.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shining</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shining
<hw>Shin"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Emission or reflection of
light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shiningness</ent>⟦br⟧
